The exclusive Cobblestone texture further enhances all Hogue stocks by providing an efficient non-slip, non irritating stippling pattern. OverMolded Stocks are constructed by molding a super strong, rigid fiberglass reinforced skeleton or "insert" that precisely fits the guns' action. This rigid skeleton is then OverMolded with a durable but soft synthetic elastomer (rubber). During the heat and extreme pressure of injection molding the elastomer adheres chemically as well as mechanically to the skeleton, resulting in a permanent bond between the rubber and the insert. The super strong skeleton gives the stocks their strength, and the precise molded dimensions provide a perfect drop-in fit of your rifle or shotgun. The state of the art elastomer material used on Hogue stocks won't harden with age and is virtually impervious to all oils and solvents found around firearms, providing years of dependable service.

title: For Sale:  M1850 Horstman Foot Officers Sword, Kepi
postcontent: Captain Frederick Ranger 22nd Regiment NY A Beautiful rare example of Old World Quality and Craftsmanship the Model 1850 Foot Officer’s Ray Skin gripped sword with its fine Blade was likely Manufactured by the Renowned firm of Gerbruder Weyersberg of Solingen, Prussia. Assembled by the celebrated importer William H. Horstmann of Philadelphia. Horstmann was a Top Tier sword Retailer and Importer who contracted with the Prussian firm for most of there better, high quality swords. Horstmann imported and assembled the blades with grips and then applied there name on the ricasso. The Majestic high-quality steel blade is slightly curved and both flats of the blade were intricately acid etched with floral decorations along with military motifs. Most etchings have lost detail due to age and battlefield use. The Ricasso on the blade obverse exhibits the retailers mark that reads HORSTMAN and SONS the other reads PHILADELPHIA (see photo's) Blade back exhibits a pleasing mottled silver gray patina with some expected pitting and oxidation. The remarkably crafted ornate cast brass hilt is authentic to a foot officer’s sword and displays an awesome floral decorated guard with a single band integrated into the knuckle bow. The Handsome ornate hilt has swelled grips in Very good condition that feature a fine ray - skin covered wooden handle that does have a few expected worn spots. Grip secured with double twisted original brass wire that has remained tight and intact. The Piece exhibits a very pleasing floral casting that let's one easily identify the superlative craftsmanship and the All original Pommel shows a single-domed cap with a beautifully constructed oak leaf design along the edges. All the brass has acquired the kind of bronze patina one hopes to find. A very obvious rare quality weapon, This Horstman Sword is a truly elegant and historic piece that provides that unique pride of ownership that we as collectors yearn to find but seldom do. As we all know only too well the highly sought after artifacts are either unavailable or seldom within our financial reach as they quietly pass from one collection to the next with few opportunities to purchase, This is one of the few occasions to acquire one well within the range of affordability and just to further eliminate any last shred of doubt you may have. This Private Purchase Kepi is Very sound and solid overall with some tiny moth holes. (SEE PHOTOS) Remarkably it has retained its original chin strap and Deep Indigo Blue that the most avid collectors insist on. Brass Federal buttons are attached which have turned to an exquisite antique brass shade. Beautiful Blue cloth patina throughout shows a piece that was lovingly cared for with slight or no damage of any consequence we could find. The leather presents with less crazing then associated with Kepi's of this age. Kepi has no separated pieces and hand stitching is firm, tight and intact. Lining is of the custom private purchase butternut which was so popular among officers and troops. No large tears or holes were found, the sweat band shows expected wear (see Photos). A truly wonderful piece in excellent all around condition that shows little age. Another piece of grace and character that along with the above artifact will without doubt make for a an envious display. The trumpet is not attached to the hat. It still has the pins on it.The price is firm and no trades please
